# How to Build LinM from Source

## Requirements

### Build Tools

- A C++ compiler with C++11 support (GCC 7+ or Clang 5+)
- [CMake](https://cmake.org) >= 3.10

### Required Libraries

- [ncurses / ncursesw](https://www.gnu.org/software/ncurses/ncurses.html) >= 5.3
  ncursesw is preferred for UTF-8 encoding support.

### Optional Libraries

- [OpenSSL](https://www.openssl.org) >= 1.0 (for SFTP support)
- [libssh2](https://www.libssh2.org) >= 1.4.0 (for SFTP support)
- [libsmbclient](https://www.samba.org) (for SMB/CIFS support)

### Installing Dependencies

Ubuntu / Debian:

    sudo apt install build-essential cmake libncursesw5-dev libssl-dev libssh2-1-dev libsmbclient-dev

Fedora / RHEL:

    sudo dnf install gcc-c++ cmake ncurses-devel openssl-devel libssh2-devel libsmbclient-devel

## Building

    mkdir build
    cd build
    cmake ..
    make -j$(nproc)

## CMake Options

    -DCMAKE_INSTALL_PREFIX=PATH   Change the installation prefix (default: /usr/local)
    -DPTHREAD_ENABLE=OFF          Build without pthread support
    -DCMAKE_BUILD_TYPE=Debug      Enable debug build

## Installing

    sudo make install

Executables are installed to ${CMAKE_INSTALL_PREFIX}/bin (default: /usr/local/bin).
Configuration files are installed to /etc/linm (system-wide) or $HOME/.linm (per-user).

To have the shell prompt return to the directory where you ended LinM,
re-login after installation.
